</paragraph>
<paragraph id="7365745B550CFFF58E5FF787FB619B8D" blockId="36.[826,1167,414,436]" box="[826,1167,414,436]" pageId="36" pageNumber="258">
<emphasis id="41AEA849550CFFF58E5FF787FC369B8A" box="[826,984,414,435]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="258">Flight period:</emphasis>
June and July.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="7365745B550CFFF58E5FF7C5FB349874" blockId="36.[826,1441,476,590]" pageId="36" pageNumber="258">
<emphasis id="41AEA849550CFFF58E5FF7C5FC569BC8" box="[826,952,476,497]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="258">Etymology:</emphasis>
Derived from the Latin ‘amplius’ meaning ‘larger’. 
<taxonomicName id="B4DA0FD8550CFFF58EC5F7E3FB179836" authorityName="Davis &amp; Gentili-Poole &amp; Mitter" authorityYear="2008" box="[928,1273,506,527]" class="Insecta" family="Cossidae" genus="Simplicivalva" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="36" pageNumber="258" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ampliophilobia">
<emphasis id="41AEA849550CFFF58EC5F7E3FB179836" box="[928,1273,506,527]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="258">Simplicivalva ampliophilobia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
refers to the larger size of this species as compared with the very similar, smaller species 
<taxonomicName id="B4DA0FD8550CFFF58931F421FB3D9874" authorityName="Druce" authorityYear="1898" box="[1108,1235,568,589]" class="Insecta" family="Cossidae" genus="Arbela" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="36" pageNumber="258" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="philobia">
<emphasis id="41AEA849550CFFF58931F421FB3D9874" box="[1108,1235,568,589]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="258">S. philobia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="7365745B550CFFF58E5FF46FFB2F997A" blockId="36.[826,1441,630,835]" pageId="36" pageNumber="258">
<emphasis id="41AEA849550CFFF58E5FF46FFC5498B2" box="[826,954,630,651]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="258">Discussion:</emphasis>
This species most closely resembles two species not known to occur in 
<collectingCountry id="0BCD34CB550CFFF589E9F48DFAE69893" box="[1164,1288,660,682]" name="Costa Rica" pageId="36" pageNumber="258">Costa Rica</collectingCountry>
, 
<taxonomicName id="B4DA0FD8550CFFF58877F48CFA819890" authorityName="Davis &amp; Gentili-Poole &amp; Mitter" authorityYear="2008" baseAuthorityName="Clench" baseAuthorityYear="1961" box="[1298,1391,660,682]" class="Insecta" family="Cossidae" genus="Simplicivalva" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="36" pageNumber="258" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eberti">
<emphasis id="41AEA849550CFFF58877F48CFA819890" box="[1298,1391,660,682]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="258">S. eberti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="B4DA0FD8550CFFF58E5FF4AAFC5998F1" authorityName="Druce" authorityYear="1898" box="[826,951,691,712]" class="Insecta" family="Cossidae" genus="Arbela" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="36" pageNumber="258" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="philobia">
<emphasis id="41AEA849550CFFF58E5FF4AAFC5998F1" box="[826,951,691,712]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="258">S. philobia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry id="0BCD34CB550CFFF58E9EF4AAFBAA98F0" box="[1019,1092,691,713]" name="Brazil" pageId="36" pageNumber="258">Brazil</collectingCountry>
. 
<taxonomicName id="B4DA0FD8550CFFF5892AF4AAFA4F98F1" authorityName="Davis &amp; Gentili-Poole &amp; Mitter" authorityYear="2008" box="[1103,1441,691,712]" class="Insecta" family="Cossidae" genus="Simplicivalva" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="36" pageNumber="258" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ampliophilobia">
<emphasis id="41AEA849550CFFF5892AF4AAFA4F98F1" box="[1103,1441,691,712]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="258">Simplicivalva ampliophilobia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from both species by being larger in size and possessing two large, nearly contiguous, fuscous spots near the termen of the forewing. In both 
<taxonomicName id="B4DA0FD8550CFFF58875F516FA80991D" authorityName="Davis &amp; Gentili-Poole &amp; Mitter" authorityYear="2008" baseAuthorityName="Clench" baseAuthorityYear="1961" box="[1296,1390,783,804]" class="Insecta" family="Cossidae" genus="Simplicivalva" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="36" pageNumber="258" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eberti">
<emphasis id="41AEA849550CFFF58875F516FA80991D" box="[1296,1390,783,804]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="258">S. eberti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="B4DA0FD8550CFFF58E5FF537FC57997B" authorityName="Druce" authorityYear="1898" box="[826,953,813,835]" class="Insecta" family="Cossidae" genus="Arbela" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="36" pageNumber="258" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="philobia">
<emphasis id="41AEA849550CFFF58E5FF537FC57997B" box="[826,953,813,835]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="258">S. philobia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
these spots are fused.
</paragraph>
